We inferred a maximum likelihood (ML) phylogenetic tree for the min187 dataset using RAxML v.8.2.12 (

) by creating 1000 ML trees under the GTR + Gamma model (seed 260697) as chosen by ModelTestNG (

) with the outgroup set to 

P. omiscomaycus

. Support for our maximum likelihood tree was obtained from 1000 bootstraps run on the highest likelihood tree using RAxML (seed 345188). We then visualized the tree in iTOL V5 (

). Bayesian clustering inference was done using unlinked loci from our min186 data set on structure_threader (

) and STRUCTURE v. 2.3.4 (

) using default settings. We ran three replicates of each K value from 1 to 20 for the dataset. Each STRUCTURE analysis was then run for 1 x 
107
iterations, with the addition of a burn-in of 2.5 x 
106
. To determine inferred K values from the STRUCTURE analysis, we visually observed each resulting run and did not count populations with membership of less than 0.001 as inferred K. Results were then pooled by observed population membership. This observed membership was then used to estimate log likelihood. We then estimated pairwise F 
ST
(

) between these clusters using the R package Hierfstat (

) on the same unlinked loci as our STRUCTURE analysis.

Morphology. Measurements and counts are as described in
except as follows: Scale rows above the lateral line were counted anteriorly from the insertion of the first dorsal ray rather than posteriorly from the first dorsal spine ( Fig. 1 ). Lateral scales were counted to the edge of the hypural plate. In some specimens, anterior scales along the lateral line became soft or deciduous and anterior most counts were estimated from the dorsolateral scale row. Caudal peduncle scales were counted at the narrowest point on the caudal peduncle on the left side of the fish. We then doubled this number and added two more scales to account for a ventral and dorsal peduncle scale. This was done to minimize judgement error in frequenting coalescing scale rows on the dorsal surface of the caudal peduncle at the narrowest point. The addition of two scales reflects our observation of a single ventral and dorsal scale being most common. All measurements taken with a caliper to the nearest 0.1 mm . Dorsal- and anal-fin ray counts include only branched rays. This was done as we observed deeply forked terminal rays in some clear and stained and CT scanned specimens. Pectoral ray counts include the ventral most ray if the length is at least half that of the longest ray. The posterior terminus for head measurements is at the tip of the opercular spine. The postorbital measurements terminate posteriorly at this spine. All morphometric measurements are displayed in Figure 1 . Morphological and meristic data reported in species descriptions include the mean value and the range within one standard deviation. We then conducted a Principal Component Analysis (PCA) in R on 16 meristic traits from 222 specimens on a 94% complete matrix from the Southeastern United States where genetic and morphological data support the presence of sympatric species. We imputed missing data using the imputePCA function in the R package missMDA (
) and set ncp to 5.

