In this study we reexamined relationships within 

Aphredoderus

. We found higher than expected species diversity within 

Aphredoderus

. Early taxonomic work recognized two distinct subspecific forms(

). Subsequent work by 

supported this assessment and suggested a wide zone of intergradation ranging from the Pascagoula River in Mississippi to the Satilla River in 
Georgia
. Similar distribution patterns of lowland fishes present from the Mississippi River to the Atlantic slope generally does not support widespread intergrade zones within this region (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). The zone of intergradation proposed for 

Aphredoderus

was much wider than that proposed for other taxa. Our analyses suggest that rather than a zone of intergradation, there is a mosaic of distinct species with overlapping ranges.
